Some of you will already have recognized that these proceedings are not taking place in the younger hall, which has been the conventional setting for our graduation ceremonies since it opened in 1929. The younger hall is currently undergoing refurbishment. To revitalize this venue for use of future generations. We are instead celebrating these rituals in Parliament Hall on South St Ave, which refers to a much older tradition of graduation. Parliament Hall and the chamber above the King James Library commenced construction in 1612 to provide the university with its first proper library, following increasing donations of books including around 200 volumes from King James the 6th and 1st, and it was completed in 1643. Parliament Hall is so named because it housed the Scottish Parliament of 1645 to 1646, when Parliament retreated to the safety of Saint Andrews, whilst Edinburgh and much of Scotland were gripped by plague. An apt parallel to our present circumstances graduation was hosted in the ceremonial space of Parliament Hall and in the King James Library from at least 1696 until the early 20th century. The tradition of graduation extends back even further and has taken place at Saint Andrews since the second decade of the 15th century. And excellence. And in turn. To be best member of those communities that you can be. Again, congratulations to all of you. Thank you very much to doctor Laila Hussein for that memorable contribution. I will now add some remarks of my own to conclude today's ceremony, and here I speak directly to our new graduates, for whom my first message is one of emphatic congratulations. The degree you have received was not easily earned. It acknowledges months or years of hard work, focus and discipline, but you have triumphed and you are now a Saint Andrews graduate. Nobody can take that accomplishment away from you. I recognize that your cohort in particular has overcome unique challenges. Since March, the COVID-19 pandemic has, as we all know, radically affected the way each of us lives and works. You are the first generation of students in my lifetime who have been unable to browse the University of Saint Andrews Library shelves, or even when the pandemic first struck access, study space or laboratories. Research requires concentration over a long period and you have sustained this while adapting to radically shifting circumstances and varying access to resources. You have special cause to be proud of the way you have overcome these difficulties. Research by its very nature makes you adaptable. It requires you to think round issues, to consider a variety of sources or inputs and to innovate in order to attain results. It requires mental agility. Your graduating class has needed to demonstrate a much higher capacity for adaptation than many which have gone before it, and you are as a result, extraordinarily capable people. You can perform highly whilst traversing uncharted terrain. You are dynamic and fortitude anous you have the capability to confront challenges and to overcome them. Those are indispensable skills because your lives will be filled with challenges. You will face tasks and projects in the workplace to which you will need to step U. You will face upheavals in your personal life. Although I hope these are few in number. You will find that you can draw on the resilience the invention, the hope, and the new companionship which you have built and exhibited in the past few months. You have got through these times and they will become an important part of you as the place in which you experience them will too. Your experiences and skills mean that as graduates you have the ability to address these challenges when they arise and to identify the wider societal issues which stand to benefit from interventions by people with your education and expertise. The challenges you choose to confront are up to you, as are the ways you confront them. You can run for public office or like Doctor Hussain found a charity. Alternatively you can integrate small acts of kindness or advocacy into your daily life. I know that this is a significant request. It takes audacity to enact change, and it is certainly much easier to do nothing. But helping others is a nobler way to use your education and leads to a more fulfilling life. Meeting these lofty standards requires courage and inspiration models for which can be found at every turn. A source of continual inspiration to me is Nelson Mandela, known to you all as the first black president of the Republic of South Africa, a role he assumed after 27 years of incarceration as a consequence of his retaliation against an oppressive apartheid regime. Mandela's legacy is recorded in his writing, most notably the Long Walk to Freedom, which I wholeheartedly recommend to you all, and in the many dramatizations of his life. Foremost amongst these is the 2009 film Invictus, directed by Clint Eastwood and starring Morgan Freeman as Nelson Mandela. It dramatizes Mandela's first term in office and charts his efforts to foster interracial alliances and partnerships in a country marked by the legacies of apartheid. Mandela exercised an almost unimaginable capacity to forgive the white citizens of South Africa who persecuted him. If I cannot change when circumstances demand it, how can I expect others to? Mandela says in Invictus? These are words to live by. The title of the film Invictus is derived from a poem of the same name written in 1875 by the Victorian poet William Ernest Henley, who received an honorary doctorate from the University of Saint Andrews in 1893. It is a short poem, 4 stanzas and 16 lines in total, and many of you will be familiar with its closing stanza. It matters not how straight the gate, how charged with punishments the screw. I am the master of my fate. I am the captain of my soul. Henry's poem expresses the Uncontrollability of resilience and determination and a conviction that one can and must overcome the challenges one faces despite their scale, one can see why Mandela found it to be such a source of potent inspiration. He memorized its lines and during his time at Robben Island Prison, recited the poem to himself and his fellow prisoners. The poem has since assumed an enormous cultural legacy, particularly in the civil rights movement. It served also as inspiration to the late Congressman John Lewis, and it was read by Barack Obama at the memorial service for Mandela in South Africa upon his death in December 2013. The film Invictus depicts Mandela's efforts to build an interracial alliance with Francois Pienaar, captain of the Springboks South Africa's national rugby union team. We find another link here because Francois Pienaar visited St. Andrews at the end of 2017 alongside fellow rugby player Sean Fitzpatrick and footballer Lilian Thuram. A triad of world champions who were advocating for the power of sport to improve life for people around the world. In Invictus, Mandela gives the poem to Francois and he says we need inspiration Francois because in order to build our nation we must all exceed our own expectations. Your time in Saint Andrews has served as a source of inspiration and it will go on doing so throughout your lives. But you must see can find other sources of inspiration, whether that is an artistic works, real world events like Mandela's story or in the example set by your fellow students, graduates and family members. Models for inspiration can be found everywhere. Identifying what inspires you will hold you in good stead as you strive to make a difference. It will, in Mandela's parlance, enable you to exceed your own expectations. For Saint Andrews student, that translates to the belief that inspiration will enable you ever to excel. I speak on behalf of your tutors, your peers and your families. When I say that you are people with boundless potential. So take today to celebrate your successes you have earned that right, but tomorrow, look around, identify your inspirations and hold these in mind as you move forward with the knowledge that you have the ability to affect great change. You are the master of your fate. Do with it what you should. Oremus Grazia Domini Nostri Yasuke Christi, at Caritas de at Communicatio Spiritus Sancti Sitkum, omnibus nobis in secular secular Orum Ahmed.
